    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Moment of Decision: The Vote on China Trade</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Brent Irvin letter disputes May 20 letters on granting China membership in World Trade Organization (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Does China Deserve Trade Status?'' (letters, May 20): If Congress rejects permanent normal trading relations with China, that will not prevent China from entering the World Trade Organization. Rather, it will simply allow Beijing to legally exclude American companies from the trade liberalization measures it is required to set up upon entering the trade body. In addition, Congressional oversight of a sovereign country is little more than political showmanship and has little or no effect on Chinese domestic policy.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Does China Deserve Trade Status?'' (letters, May 20): If Congress rejects permanent normal trading relations with China, that will not prevent China from entering the World Trade Organization. Rather, it will simply allow Beijing to legally exclude American companies from the trade liberalization measures it is required to set up upon entering the trade body. In addition, Congressional oversight of a sovereign country is little more than political showmanship and has little or no effect on Chinese domestic policy.</p>
        <p>Of those within China in the best position to understand and feel the effects of this debate, many environmental, human rights and democracy activists in China see the granting of permanent normal trading privileges as a tool for progressive change within China.</p>
        <p>BRENT IRVIN  Bloomington, Minn., May 20, 2000</p>
      </block>
